>> > > > > > > > > > > The reason for the obsession here is that I can
>> > > > parallelise basically
>> > > > > > > > > > > all steps in the whole algorithm *except* those steps for
>> > > > which I need
>> > > > > > > > > > > to take a determinant. There are two such steps:
>> > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > 1) to get the saturated propagator, you need to invert
>> > > > the matrices
>> > > > > > > > > > > and
>> > > > > > > > > > > therefore a Det is implicit.
>> > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > 2) to get the massless eigenvalues, you need to do
>> > > > something which is
>> > > > > > > > > > > necessarily equivalent to computing a Det.
>> > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > These two kinds of Det are very different, but in both
>> > > > cases it is
>> > > > > > > > > > > important that the symbolic object I'm taking Det of is
>> > > > as simple as
>> > > > > > > > > > > humanly possible..
