>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > I will tell you more
>> > > > when things are settled.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Some answers below.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Il 14/10/2023 02:20,
>> > > > Will Barker ha scritto:
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Dear Roberto,
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Carlo, Sebastian
>> > > > and I finally fixed a meeting for next week, so I hope
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > we can all have a
>> > > > useful discussion about the PGT renormalisation then,
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > and make a proper
>> > > > reply to your earlier mail.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > In the meantime,
>> > > > Damianos Iosifidis (cc) and I have been working for
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > some weeks on the
>> > > > spectrum of unrestricted, parity-preserving MAG. When
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > we fed the full
>> > > > theory into the software, there were some `digestive'
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > problems, so we
>> > > > have since been working on the model in which all the
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > a_1 through a_11
>> > > > couplings are vanishing, i.e. the general F+F^2 theory.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Well, it's a pretty
>> > > > general theory but certainly not the most general,
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > as you also set to
>> > > > zero all the DT^2, RDT etc terms.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Even in this case I
>> > > > have had some difficulty with the massless limit of
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > the symmetries and
>> > > > constraints, so at the moment only the massive poles
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > are clear (see
>> > > > attached scrap of TeX, the numerator of the square 1^-
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > mass is a long
>> > > > quadratic in the c_i parameters which I do not write in
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > full).
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > I'm concerned about
>> > > > the relative paucity of spectra to compare with in
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > the literature, so
>> > > > Damianos was hoping to confirm our findings at the
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > level of the field
>> > > > equations.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > However, during our
>> > > > meeting today we realised with shame that we weren't
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > really familiar
>> > > > with spin-3 field theory! We re-watched your lecture [1]
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > from Tartu, and
>> > > > found that we should be looking for the Fronsdal action.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > However, whilst my
>> > > > software is (necessarily) sensitive to this structure
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > in the linear
>> > > > theory, Damianos' methods rely on the full, nonlinear MAG,
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > without
>> > > > post-Riemannian expansion.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Fronsdal is massless.
>> > > > If you want the massive case you have to look
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > for
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Singh-Hagen.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > At linearized level
>> > > > we have discussed this (as well as the 2- case) in
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Annals Phys. 438
>> > > > (2022) 168757 • e-Print: 2112.10193 [gr-qc]
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > The construction of
>> > > > interactions for Fronsdal field is long standing
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > and
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > difficult problem
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > and the higher-spin
>> > > > people have barely managed to construct a
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > three-vertex.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Higher vertices are
>> > > > not known.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Therefore, we're
>> > > > curious as to whether the generalisation of Fronsdal is
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > known, for general
>> > > > connections? For example in the case of the
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > homothetic square
>> > > > operator, the linearised and covariant kinetic
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > structures are
>> > > > identical because of the antisymmetry in the Maxwell
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > tensor. Therefore
>> > > > the linearisation is not very laborious (and there is
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > a non-accidental
>> > > > symmetry). However, I suppose that if I simply
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > covariantise the
>> > > > derivative operators in Fronsdal, many extra quadratic
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > interactions will
>> > > > be picked up, allowing for the spin-3 mode to couple
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > to other
>> > > > torsion/nonmetric fields in complicated ways?
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Covariantizing
>> > > > Fronsdal by a minimal coupling prescription generates
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > infinitely many
>> > > > vertices in one go and the chances that they are
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > consistent are very
>> > > > slim.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Same if you just
>> > > > start from some (fully nonlinear) MAG action
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > that countains a
>> > > > propagating spin 3 when linearized around flat space.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > There is a paper of
>> > > > Baekler and Hehl that does something of the sort,
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > but we do not think
>> > > > that is is ok at nonlinear level.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > I have been working
>> > > > on this issue with Sezgin for a while.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > I have ways to test
>> > > > for this kind of effect, simply by checking whether
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > the shift symmetry
>> > > > is broken in the nonlinear model (I can automate
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > that). However, in
>> > > > the case that the symmetry is not broken (a
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > miracle?), it would
>> > > > be best to justify the result by Damianos' being
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > able to point out
>> > > > the `known nonlinear extension of spin-3' in the field
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > equations, or
>> > > > something like that. My method is brute-force, but
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Damianos' is more
>> > > > connected to the physics of the model, and more
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > satisfying.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > So my question is,
>> > > > how well is the spin-3 sector understood? Is it just
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > understood in the
>> > > > way that Fierz-Pauli is, without attempts at nonlinear
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > extension? Could
>> > > > you also say how well the massive spin-3 is understood
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > (and whether the
>> > > > Bellazzini paper is still the cutting edge of this
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > topic)?
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > See above.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > I will be in touch
>> > > > when I have something to add.
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Best
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > Roberto
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > >
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > For the 2^- sector
>> > > > I seem to recall that the literature to look at is
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > that of the
>> > > > Curtright field, but similarly, I'm not sure if the string
>> > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > > theorists have put
>> > > > this in curved backgrounds etc.
